 concerned with social justice. They examine key turning points in the given association's history and explore how its mandate, leadership, relationship to the federal and provincial governments, and shifting options in the political arena shaped its response to linguistic diversity. Language Matters provides a deeper understanding of the language dynamic in Canada and offers solutions to groups and governments trying to manage difference.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAssociationsxCanada. 0aAssociations, institutions, etcxCanada. 0aAssociations, institutions, etczCanada. 0aAssociations, institutions, etc.zCanada. 0aBilingualismxCanada. 0aBilingualismzCanada. 0aBilinguismexCanada. 0aLanguage policyxCanada. 0aLanguage policyzCanada. 0aPolitique linguistiquexCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Cultural Policy.2bisacsh1 aBlacklock, Cathy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, David R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCameron, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDugas, Sylvie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuquette, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilbert, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenson, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaforest, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMau, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimeon, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimeon, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vo